## 6. Debugging History & Failure Modes — ✅ High

- A temporary browser-proof `.env` changed demo ports and leaked into two launcher unit tests. Root cause was ambient project configuration, not product logic. The file and temporary SQLite/CSV proof artifacts were removed; a clean rerun passed.
- Streamlit's switch input could not be toggled with a low-level checked-state call in the browser harness; clicking its unique visible label worked and the checked state was verified from a fresh DOM snapshot.
- Multipart parsing initially looked convenient but could spool to disk before application limits ran. The route now streams a bounded raw body.
- Template case mappings were initially opaque result IDs; case order/external labels were added for reviewer usability while immutable IDs remain the verification anchor.
- Adding display mapping fields to canonical hashes caused JSON/CSV identity drift; display fields are verified but excluded from the canonical label identity.
- Float signed zero could create different hashes for equivalent thresholds/scores; canonical numeric normalization fixed it.
- Database-level candidate/run integrity required a composite relationship, not service-only checks.
- GitHub main CI emitted cache-reservation annotations from parallel jobs. Treat as benign only when every required job is successful; never suppress a real failure under that explanation.

